# x86-64 Endianness, Memory Layout & Reversing Cheat Sheet

## Endianness

### Little Endian (x86/x86-64)

Multi-byte values are stored with the **least significant byte first**.

Example:

```text
Value:
0x12345678

Memory:
78 56 34 12
```

---

### Big Endian

```text
Value:
0x12345678

Memory:
12 34 56 78
```

---

## Memory → Register

### WORD (2 bytes)

Memory:

```text
34 12
```

Instruction:

```asm
mov ax, [rdi]
```

Register:

```text
ax = 0x1234
```

---

### DWORD (4 bytes)

Memory:

```text
78 56 34 12
```

Instruction:

```asm
mov eax, [rdi]
```

Register:

```text
eax = 0x12345678
```

---

### QWORD (8 bytes)

Memory:

```text
88 77 66 55 44 33 22 11
```

Instruction:

```asm
mov rax, [rdi]
```

Register:

```text
rax = 0x1122334455667788
```

---

# Size Reference

| Name  | Bits | Bytes | Register |
| ----- | ---- | ----- | -------- |
| byte  | 8    | 1     | al       |
| word  | 16   | 2     | ax       |
| dword | 32   | 4     | eax      |
| qword | 64   | 8     | rax      |

---

# Register Hierarchy

```text
rax = 64 bits

┌──────────────────────────────┐
│            rax               │
└──────────────────────────────┘

            eax (32 bits)

                ax (16 bits)

                 al (8 bits)
```

Example:

```text
rax = 1122334455667788

eax =         55667788

ax  =             7788

al  =               88
```

